Escape from Moscow
The fall of communism gave the nations of the former Soviet bloc the opportunity to turn towards democracy, the market economy, and the rule of law.
Some of these countries decisively broke off ties with their communist past; others were less successful, and a few have catastrophically failed.
Moldova and Georgia belonged to the aforementioned category until recently.
Your economic and political failure largely resulted from — actively supported by Russia — secessionist movements that tried to keep both countries within the "sphere of influence" of the Kremlin.
When bloody conflicts erupted in Transnistria, Abkhazia, and South Ossetia, Russia transformed its military presence there into "peacekeeping forces" to maintain control.
For a long time, people have feared that these so-called "frozen conflicts" could suddenly turn into hot conflicts.
Not only did this not happen, but now we can talk about solutions – for both Georgia and Moldova have begun to make progress toward a market economy and democracy.
This has also been contributed to by the European Union's "neighborhood policy."
The starting point of these developments was the "Rose Revolution" in Georgia three years ago.
Already dangerously close to a failed state, Georgia has since turned towards the West.
The success of various "color revolutions" in former Soviet countries also triggered a change in Moldova. There, President Vladimir Voronin initiated reforms aimed at closer alignment with the EU.
These changes have triggered new initiatives in Georgia and Moldova to restore the territorial integrity of these countries in a peaceful manner.
Estonia's experience suggests how Georgia and Moldova should shape their policies toward Russia.
When Estonia gained independence in 1991, Moscow sought to portray Estonia as a country with massive economic problems, unsuitable for investments.
Estonia was indeed poor, and its most important export products were scrap metal and timber, yet its economy grew.
In North-East Estonia, with its predominantly Russian-speaking population, which had settled here during the Soviet era, Russia supported a so-called "autonomy movement."
When Estonia resisted, Russia imposed sanctions and cut off gas supplies.
High taxes were imposed on the few Estonian products that were allowed to be imported into Russia, and Russia even threatened military intervention.
But Estonia kept its nerve.
The Russian sanctions even helped the country to realign its economy towards the West.
Western Europe, on the other hand, did what it could to integrate the Baltic states—Lithuania, Latvia, and Estonia—and at the same time tried to avoid a conflict with Russia.
In 1994, a free trade agreement with the EU enabled Estonian products to find new markets, and thus Estonia ultimately became one of the most successful postcommunist transition countries and joined the EU and NATO in 2004.
When Georgia gained independence in 1991, it was not supported in the same way by Western Europe.
Indeed, Georgia appeared less attractive as a partner compared to the Baltic states; the 1990s were marked by coups, counter-coups, and civil wars, during which two regions—Abkhazia and South Ossetia—effectively seceded with the support of Russia.
The country did its best to forget its bleak past.
Since the Rose Revolution, the economy has been reformed, the army has been strengthened, and the leadership of the country is young, dynamic, and diligently working to advance the country.
Thanks to Georgia's flat income tax of 12% – likely the lowest in the world – the national budget has increased.
The government has raised pensions and increased social benefits.
Corruption is decreasing, and a judicial reform has been initiated.
The economy grew by 8% in 2005 and by more than 10% in 2006.
Georgia is trying to ease the tensions around Abkhazia and South Ossetia; however, Russia accuses the country of aggression as well as ethnic cleansing.
His main goal is to prevent the West from supporting Georgia and to block reconciliation with the separatist regions.
The powers that matter in Georgia are Russia and to a certain extent the United States.
Europe must show that it is also important.
Estonia has shown - at the time of its independence and again during the recent crisis over the relocation of a Soviet-era monument - that one can resist Russian pressure with determination and strong support.
Europe must understand that Georgia needs trade, not humanitarian aid.
Just as the free trade agreement with Europe enabled Estonia to find new markets, this can be the means by which Georgians can help themselves.
Georgia has legitimate reasons to hope that it will achieve real independence. But what about Moldova, the poorest country in Europe, which is more strongly threatened by Russia than the Estonians or even the Georgians ever were?
The lack of reform successes is partly the result of secessionist movements supported by Russia.
The fact that the industrialized region of Transnistria—whose Russian- and Ukrainian-speaking population feared the majority of Moldavians, who are of Romanian descent, planned closer ties with Romania—severed ties with Moldova dealt the country's independence a severe blow right from the beginning.
A civil war followed, and in 1992 Russian troops marched into Transnistria, where they are still stationed today.
The independence of Transnistria was never recognized – neither by Moldova nor internationally.
It is said that there is lawlessness and corruption there.
The Moldau is heavily in debt, unemployment is high, and its once-renowned wine industry is in decline.
Russia occasionally suspends gas deliveries, and many of the four million citizens have left the country.
Only Russia can solve the problem.
Moldovan government representatives have made four fruitless visits to Moscow to persuade President Vladimir Putin to make efforts toward a solution and to withdraw Russian troops.
A desperate Voronin has asked the EU observer force Eubam for help, but would require a EU initiative for Russian cooperation.
Unfortunately, it seems that the West lacks up-to-date knowledge about the situation in Moldova.
For example, in April, both the EU and the USA first learned of a proposed peace agreement through a report that had leaked from Germany.
This, it seems, would benefit Russia, since Moldova is supposed to recognize Transnistria as a legitimate entity.
If Russia has stabbed the West in this way, it would be a disastrous precedent for Georgia and other weak post-communist states.
